"""
MKT Christ Commentary — 2 Kings chapters 21–23
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-2kings-21-23.py

Ch21: Manasseh — the covenant failure that even Josiah cannot reverse; innocent blood (v16)
Ch22: Josiah finds the Law — the word rediscovered; Huldah's oracle; the humble king
Ch23: Josiah's reform — covenant renewal; Passover restored; nevertheless-clause (v26);
      death at Megiddo; rapid post-Josiah collapse

Key typological connections:
- 21:4: 'In Jerusalem I will put my Name' → John 1:14 (Word tabernacling among us)
- 21:6: child sacrifice / Molech → antithesis of John 3:16; the Father gives rather than demands
- 21:16: innocent blood fills Jerusalem → Matt 27:25; the ultimate innocent blood
- 22:2: Josiah turns neither right nor left → Heb 4:15 (Jesus without sin, no exception clause)
- 22:8: Torah found in the temple → John 1:14; the Word dwelling among his people
- 22:19: Josiah humbled himself → Phil 2:8; the humble king type
- 23:3: covenant renewal with all heart/soul → Heb 9:15 (Christ mediator of the new covenant)
- 23:10: Topheth/Gehenna → Matt 5:22 (Jesus uses 'Gehenna' for eschatological fire)
- 23:15-16: 1 Kgs 13:2 fulfilled after 300 years → prophetic word not bound by time
- 23:21-23: Passover restored → 1 Cor 5:7 (Christ our Passover lamb)
- 23:25-26: greatest king + 'nevertheless' → Heb 10:4 (no reform can atone; only Christ can)
- 23:29: Josiah killed at Megiddo → death of the righteous king; Rev 16:16
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(layer, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

CHRIST = {
  "21": {
    "1": "<p>Manasseh: twelve years old at accession, fifty-five years on the throne — the longest reign in Judean history, son of Hezekiah, who had the most faithful record. The immediate succession of maximum faithfulness (Hezekiah) by maximum unfaithfulness (Manasseh) is a warning embedded in the narrative: the covenant privilege of the redeemed community produces the sharpest apostasy when abandoned. The measuring standard of the Davidic covenant — David himself — proved insufficient to transmit faithfulness across generations. What is needed is not a better David or a longer chain of Davids but the one David pointed toward: the king whose faithfulness is constitutive of his identity rather than dependent on it.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Manasseh followed the <em>tôʿăḇōt</em> of the nations YHWH had expelled. The Canaanite nations expelled for their abominations are now his explicit models. The inversion of the covenant purpose — Israel was to be a light to the nations, demonstrating YHWH&rsquo;s way — is total: the covenant people are below the covenant-free pagans they replaced. This is the structure of every unredeemed religious community: the covenant that was meant to create distinctiveness becomes the occasion for greater darkness when abandoned (cf. Matt 11:23-24: Capernaum, where the miracles were done, will be judged more severely than Sodom).</p>",
    "3": "<p>Manasseh rebuilds what Hezekiah demolished. The reformer&rsquo;s son dismantles the reform. The instability of all human reform not grounded in changed hearts: the next generation can undo what the previous generation built. Jer 31:33: the new covenant will not be like the Sinai covenant — it will be written on the heart, not on stone tablets that the next generation can ignore. Josiah&rsquo;s reform will face the same problem: his sons immediately revert. The covenant written on stone cannot transform the heart; only the Spirit can (Ezek 36:26-27).</p>",
    "4": "<p>&ldquo;In Jerusalem I will put my Name.&rdquo; The Name-theology drives the entire temple ideology: YHWH&rsquo;s self-giving through his Name (<em>šēm</em>) to a specific place is the OT form of the Incarnation&rsquo;s logic. John 1:14: &ldquo;The Word became flesh and <em>skenosen</em> — tabernacled — among us.&rdquo; The Name that dwelt in the Jerusalem temple becomes the Name made flesh in Jesus. Manasseh&rsquo;s desecration of the Name&rsquo;s dwelling anticipates every act that seeks to displace or defile the presence of the incarnate Son (John 2:19: &ldquo;destroy this temple, and in three days I will raise it up&rdquo;).</p>",
    "5": "<p>Altars to the host of heaven in both courts — the astral cult of Mesopotamian religion. The worship of the created lights instead of the Creator (Rom 1:25: &ldquo;they worshiped and served the creature rather than the Creator&rdquo;) is the primordial form of idolatry (cf. Rom 1:21-23: the descent from knowing God to worshiping birds, four-footed animals, and reptiles). The host of heaven that Manasseh worships are the objects of YHWH&rsquo;s creative power (Gen 1:14-18: the lights he made to govern day and night). Worshiping the creation YHWH rules rather than the ruler himself is the root of all human religious error.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Child sacrifice to Molech — <em>heʿĕḇîr ʾet bᵉnô bāʾēš</em>. Manasseh sacrifices his own son. The direct antithesis of John 3:16: &ldquo;God so loved the world that he gave his only Son.&rdquo; Molech demands the child&rsquo;s death to secure the father&rsquo;s prosperity; YHWH gives his own Son&rsquo;s death to secure the world&rsquo;s life. The two sacrifice logics are exact inversions: Molech worship is the human projection of a divine claim on children; the gospel is the divine absorption of the human claim on the Son. The list of prohibited practices (divination, omens, mediums, spiritists) all represent attempts to secure information and power outside of YHWH&rsquo;s covenant — the religion of control instead of trust.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The carved Asherah pole placed inside the temple — the fertility goddess installed at the address of YHWH&rsquo;s Name. The desecration of the holy of holies-precinct by placing a rival deity there is the OT&rsquo;s form of the &ldquo;abomination of desolation&rdquo; (Dan 9:27; Matt 24:15): the holy place occupied by what is unholy. Every assertion of an alternative ultimate authority in the space consecrated to YHWH is an iteration of this pattern.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The conditional promise: &ldquo;if they carefully observe everything I commanded them.&rdquo; The <em>raq</em>-clause of the covenant — the single condition on which the entire promise of permanent land tenure depended. The condition was not met; therefore the promise was not kept. The NT equivalent is the unconditional new covenant: &ldquo;I will give you a new heart... I will put my Spirit within you and cause you to walk in my statutes&rdquo; (Ezek 36:26-27) — YHWH removes the <em>raq</em>-clause by providing the obedience himself through the Spirit.</p>",
    "9": "<p>&ldquo;Manasseh led them astray so that they did more evil than the nations YHWH had destroyed.&rdquo; The leader who uses his authority to lead the covenant community away from YHWH rather than toward him is the NT&rsquo;s false prophet, the anti-shepherd who scatters the flock (Ezek 34:1-6; John 10:12-13). Jesus: &ldquo;Whoever causes one of these little ones who believe in me to sin, it would be better for him to have a great millstone fastened around his neck and to be drowned in the depth of the sea&rdquo; (Matt 18:6). Manasseh&rsquo;s fifty-five-year anti-discipleship is the measure of that millstone.</p>",
    "10": "<p>YHWH speaks through his prophets — the sustained prophetic witness of the period (Isaiah, Micah, Zephaniah, Jeremiah). The word of judgment is not hidden but spoken, repeatedly, by multiple witnesses. 2 Pet 1:21: &ldquo;men spoke from God as they were carried along by the Holy Spirit.&rdquo; The rejection of the prophetic word is not ignorance but willful refusal of a clear and persistent witness.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The oracle names the crime: <em>ḥiqqûṣîm</em> (deeper abomination) and <em>gillûlîm</em> (dung-idols). The contemptuous vocabulary of the prophets who saw what Manasseh was doing: to call his cult objects &ldquo;dung pellets&rdquo; is to see them with YHWH&rsquo;s eyes — stripped of their prestige, reduced to their substance. Phil 3:8: Paul uses the same shock vocabulary (<em>skybala</em> — &ldquo;rubbish&rdquo; or &ldquo;dung&rdquo;) for everything he once valued outside of Christ. The gospel is the final refusal of the false prestige of all that competes with Christ.</p>",
    "12": "<p>&ldquo;The ears of everyone who hears of it will tingle.&rdquo; The disaster so great that it produces a physical shock in the mere hearing — the standard for which no historical event yet qualifies. The fall of Jerusalem in 587 BCE is the referent, but the NT applies the language of eschatological catastrophe (Rev 18:9-10: the kings of the earth stand far off, weeping, &ldquo;for in a single hour your judgment has come&rdquo;). The formula of unprecedented disaster anticipates the final judgment that exceeds every historical disaster.</p>",
    "13": "<p>&ldquo;I will stretch over Jerusalem the measuring line used against Samaria and the plumb line used against the house of Ahab; I will wipe Jerusalem as one wipes a dish.&rdquo; YHWH applies the same demolition standard to his own beloved city that he applied to the hated northern kingdom and the worst northern dynasty. The impartiality of divine judgment: no location or lineage grants immunity from the measuring line. Rom 2:11: &ldquo;God shows no partiality.&rdquo; The judgment that destroyed Samaria and the house of Ahab reaches to Jerusalem itself — the nearer to YHWH, the more exact the accounting.</p>",
    "14": "<p>&ldquo;I will abandon the remnant of my inheritance.&rdquo; YHWH abandons what he called his inheritance. The most terrible word in the oracle: the God who chose Israel as his own portion now releases it to its enemies. The cross is the NT fulfillment of this logic: Jesus cries &ldquo;My God, my God, why have you forsaken me?&rdquo; (Matt 27:46) — the abandonment of the righteous remnant, the one who is YHWH&rsquo;s true inheritance and Israel&rsquo;s true representative, in order that the abandonment might become the avenue of restoration. The abandonment of Jerusalem leads to the exile that leads to the return; the abandonment of the Son leads to the death that leads to the resurrection.</p>",
    "15": "<p>&ldquo;From the day their ancestors came out of Egypt until this day.&rdquo; The covenant failure is not new — it stretches back to the Exodus. The Deuteronomistic History&rsquo;s deepest claim: the rebellion of the covenant people is not a recent deterioration but a chronic condition of the covenant relationship from its beginning (Exod 32 — the golden calf at Sinai; Deut 9:7: &ldquo;from the day you came out of Egypt until you came to this place, you have been rebellious against the LORD&rdquo;). Rom 3:9-18: &ldquo;all, both Jews and Greeks, are under sin.&rdquo; The Manasseh oracle is the OT&rsquo;s penultimate statement of the universal sinfulness that requires a new covenant.</p>",
    "16": "<p>&ldquo;Manasseh shed so much innocent blood (<em>dām nāqî</em>) that he filled Jerusalem from end to end.&rdquo; The innocent blood that saturates the city will be invoked in 24:4 as the sin YHWH &ldquo;was not willing to pardon.&rdquo; Jerusalem, the city of David, becomes the city of innocent blood — and this trajectory reaches its climax at the crucifixion: the most innocent blood of all is shed in Jerusalem by its own leadership (Matt 27:25: &ldquo;His blood be on us and on our children&rdquo;). The accumulated innocent blood of Manasseh&rsquo;s reign is the dark context for the city&rsquo;s final act of innocent blood, through which YHWH paradoxically achieves the atonement that Manasseh&rsquo;s sins made necessary.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The regnal summary notes that Manasseh&rsquo;s sins are recorded. The historical record of Manasseh&rsquo;s crimes is permanent — it cannot be revised or erased by subsequent reform. 2 Chronicles 33:12-17 records Manasseh&rsquo;s repentance in Assyrian captivity (not mentioned in Kings) — even the worst king of Judah, in extremity, can repent. But the national consequences of his fifty-five-year reign cannot be undone even by genuine personal repentance. The distinction between personal forgiveness and corporate consequence is built into the prophetic witness about Jerusalem.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Manasseh buried in the garden of Uzza — not in the City of David. The exclusion from the royal tombs marks his distance from the covenant succession even in death. The spatial exclusion from the burial place of the covenant kings will be contrasted sharply with Josiah: a righteous king buried in his own tomb (23:30) and a wicked king buried in a garden. The place of burial in the Deuteronomistic History is a theological marker.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Amon: twenty-two years old, two years. The extreme brevity of the reign after the extreme length of Manasseh&rsquo;s mirrors the abrupt ending of dynasties built on apostasy. The covenant cannot sustain what covenant-breaking sets in motion — even the length of a reign is under YHWH&rsquo;s governance.</p>",
    "20": "<p>&ldquo;He did what was evil in the sight of YHWH, as his father Manasseh had done.&rdquo; The evaluative formula for Amon is entirely derivative — he has no independent theological significance but is the continuation and completion of his father&rsquo;s trajectory. The son who inherits the father&rsquo;s sin without the father&rsquo;s fifty-five years of entrenching it demonstrates that the pattern is systemic. The systemic sin of a dynasty can only be interrupted by a radical intervention — which is what Josiah will be.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Amon walks in all the ways of his father, worshiping the same <em>gillûlîm</em>. The inherited idolatry: the idols passed from father to son as family inheritance. The generational transmission of sin and its objects is the OT&rsquo;s anthropological realism. Exod 20:5: &ldquo;visiting the iniquity of the fathers on the children.&rdquo; The only inheritance that breaks the chain is the new birth that makes one a child of a different Father (John 1:12-13: &ldquo;born not of blood... but of God&rdquo;).</p>",
    "22": "<p>&ldquo;He abandoned (<em>ʿāzaḇ</em>) YHWH, the God of his ancestors.&rdquo; <em>ʿĀzaḇ</em> — the covenantal term for desertion, the same word YHWH will use when he announces his own abandonment of his inheritance (v14). The abandonment is reciprocal in the covenant: when the partner abandons YHWH, YHWH ultimately abandons the partner — except that his abandonment, in the case of Christ, becomes the avenue of restoration rather than final rejection.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Amon&rsquo;s officials assassinate him. The palace coup against the king points forward to the trial of Jesus: the established leadership conspires against the one whose authority they will not acknowledge. The difference is total: Amon is killed because his servants resent his rule; Jesus is killed because his enemies fear his rule. But both are killed by those whose institutional power they threaten or offend.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The <em>ʿam hāʾāreṣ</em> (people of the land) execute the conspirators and install Josiah. The same constitutional actors who have repeatedly preserved the Davidic line (11:14; 14:21; 21:24) exercise their covenantal responsibility. The preservation of the Davidic succession through the covenant community&rsquo;s non-royal members is the OT&rsquo;s recurring demonstration that YHWH&rsquo;s messianic purposes do not depend on the palace. The genealogy of Christ passes through a series of unlikely or scandalous figures precisely because the line is sustained by divine purpose rather than human virtue.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Amon&rsquo;s brief reign is noted and closed. The two verses given to Amon contrast with the extensive Josiah narrative that follows: the brevity of the wicked stands against the length of the righteous — a structural comment on their respective significance.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Amon buried in the Garden of Uzza, as his father was. The two wicked kings sharing the same burial ground outside the royal tombs are a unit — the father and son apostasy is matched by the father and son burial. The next tomb mentioned will be Josiah&rsquo;s own tomb in Jerusalem (23:30) — the contrast is structural.</p>"
  },
  "22": {
    "1": "<p>Josiah: eight years old at accession, thirty-one years on the throne. The child king installed after assassination, grown into the greatest covenant king since David. The unlikely instrument — a child, installed by the <em>ʿam hāʾāreṣ</em> after his father&rsquo;s murder — is the OT&rsquo;s structural pattern for YHWH&rsquo;s chosen: Moses in the basket, Samuel at three years old, David the youngest brother. The Name of his mother — <em>Yᵉḏîḏāh</em>, &ldquo;beloved of YHWH&rdquo; — is the program for what follows.</p>",
    "2": "<p>&ldquo;He did what was right in the sight of YHWH and followed completely the way of his ancestor David, not turning aside to the right or to the left.&rdquo; The phrase &ldquo;not turning aside to right or left&rdquo; is applied only to David and Josiah in the entire Deuteronomistic History — but David had the exception clause of Uriah (15:5). Josiah is the king with no exception clause noted — the closest the OT comes to the complete covenant faithfulness that Heb 4:15 names as Christ&rsquo;s achievement: &ldquo;one who in every respect has been tempted as we are, yet without sin.&rdquo; Josiah is the penultimate form of the type; Christ is the antitype who has no exception clause whatever.</p>",
    "3": "<p>In the eighteenth year, Josiah sends Shaphan to the temple — the administrative act of temple repair that accidentally produces the most significant theological discovery of the monarchy. YHWH&rsquo;s providential timing: the renovation of the institution leads to the rediscovery of the foundation document. The Spirit works through apparently mundane administrative actions to bring about his purposes.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Hilkiah is instructed to count the money collected in the temple. The financial administration of the covenant community&rsquo;s worship: the Temple required maintenance, the maintenance required resources, the resources required collection and accountability. The institutional infrastructure of worship is spiritually neutral until the word of God is either found or ignored within it.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The money is to be entrusted to the supervisors of the temple work. The administrative chain of trust — king to high priest to supervisors to workers — reflects the covenant community&rsquo;s structure: authority delegated in order for the work to be done. The NT parallel: Christ appoints apostles, apostles appoint elders, elders oversee deacons, the whole community serves. The structure of delegation does not diminish accountability — it distributes it appropriately.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The skilled workers — carpenters, builders, stonemasons — and materials (timber, dressed stone) are the instruments of the physical repair. The embodied, material work of maintaining the temple is as much a covenantal act as prayer: the body of the community takes care of the body of YHWH&rsquo;s dwelling. The Incarnation vindicates the body&rsquo;s importance: the Word became flesh, not merely idea.</p>",
    "7": "<p>&ldquo;They were not required to keep accounts because they were acting honestly (<em>ʾĕmet</em>).&rdquo; The community of <em>ʾĕmet</em> — faithfulness/truth — does not require the surveillance that unfaithfulness demands. The eschatological community described in Rev 21:25-27 (&ldquo;its gates will never be shut&rdquo;, nothing unclean will enter) is the ultimate form of this accountability-free trust: the new Jerusalem does not need locks because nothing in it can betray the trust.</p>",
    "8": "<p>&ldquo;I have found the Book of the Law in the house of YHWH.&rdquo; The Torah buried in the Temple — the foundation document of the covenant, lost within the covenant institution itself. The rediscovery is at once an indictment and a gift: the word that could have prevented everything Manasseh did was present in the house all along, waiting to be found. John 5:39: &ldquo;You search the Scriptures because you think that in them you have eternal life; and it is they that bear witness about me.&rdquo; The Scriptures were present; their witness was not heard. The finding of the law under Josiah is the OT&rsquo;s type of every generation&rsquo;s rediscovery that the word was there all along.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Shaphan reports the administrative completion first, then the book — the word comes embedded in the ordinary report of ordinary administrative work. The word of God does not always arrive with fanfare; it comes through normal human communication, requiring the listener to recognize its significance. The disciples hearing Jesus teaching in parables: the word came through ordinary speech, and &ldquo;to you it has been given to know the secrets of the kingdom of heaven, but to them it has not been given&rdquo; (Matt 13:11).</p>",
    "10": "<p>Shaphan reads the book aloud to the king. The oral reading of Scripture before the community — <em>miqrāʾ</em>, &ldquo;calling out/public reading&rdquo; — is the covenant&rsquo;s primary mode of transmission. Deut 31:11-13: the Torah is to be read aloud to all Israel every seven years. Neh 8:8: &ldquo;they read from the book, from the Law of God, clearly, and they gave the sense, so that the people understood the reading.&rdquo; 1 Tim 4:13: &ldquo;devote yourself to the public reading of Scripture.&rdquo;</p>",
    "11": "<p>When the king heard the words of the Book of the Law, he tore his clothes. The hearing of the word of judgment produces the physical expression of grief and conviction. 2 Cor 7:10: &ldquo;godly grief produces a repentance that leads to salvation without regret.&rdquo; Josiah&rsquo;s immediate physical response to the word — he does not debate, rationalize, or delay — is the model of genuine reception of the word of judgment. The word that cuts to the heart (Acts 2:37: &ldquo;When they heard this they were cut to the heart&rdquo;) produces the outward response of grief before it produces the inward response of repentance.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Josiah dispatches a five-person delegation to &ldquo;inquire of YHWH.&rdquo; The prophetic consultation (<em>dāraš ʾet YHWH</em>) is the covenant community&rsquo;s mechanism for receiving the word in real time. The delegation is senior (high priest, court officials, secretary) — Josiah takes the word seriously enough to send his best people. The seriousness with which one treats the word of God is the measure of one&rsquo;s actual relationship to the God of the word.</p>",
    "13": "<p>&ldquo;Great is YHWH&rsquo;s anger that burns against us because our ancestors did not obey the words of this book, to do everything written for us.&rdquo; Josiah&rsquo;s framing is notable: he says &ldquo;our ancestors&rdquo; and &ldquo;for us&rdquo; — he identifies with the sin of the past rather than disowning it. The confession that the past generation&rsquo;s sin has consequences for the present generation is not fatalism but covenantal realism. Dan 9:5-8: Daniel&rsquo;s prayer confesses &ldquo;we have sinned... to us belongs open shame&rdquo; — the righteous man identifies with the community&rsquo;s failure. This is the structure of Christ&rsquo;s vicarious identification: he who knew no sin was made sin for us (2 Cor 5:21).</p>",
    "14": "<p>Hilkiah and the delegation go to Huldah the prophetess. The Spirit&rsquo;s choice of a woman as the authorized interpreter of the Torah at the most pivotal moment of the monarchy is deliberate. The pattern of the Spirit appointing unexpected voices — Miriam, Deborah, Huldah, the Samaritan woman at the well, Mary Magdalene at the resurrection — undermines every claim that divine authorization follows human social hierarchies. The Spirit &ldquo;blows where he wishes&rdquo; (John 3:8).</p>",
    "15": "<p>&ldquo;This is what YHWH, the God of Israel, says.&rdquo; Huldah speaks with the full prophetic authority formula — not &ldquo;this is my interpretation&rdquo; or &ldquo;this is what I think,&rdquo; but the divine messenger formula that marks authorized transmission of the divine word. The prophetess speaks as YHWH&rsquo;s voice; her authority is not her own but the one who sends her. John 7:16: &ldquo;My teaching is not mine, but his who sent me.&rdquo;</p>",
    "16": "<p>&ldquo;I am going to bring disaster on this place and its people, according to everything written in the book.&rdquo; Huldah confirms both the authenticity of the found book and the certainty of its judgment. The prophetic authentication of the Torah: the prophetess standing before the word she did not write recognizes it as YHWH&rsquo;s word and says so. The canon is not validated by councils alone but by the prophetic witness that recognizes the word&rsquo;s authority. Jesus: &ldquo;these are the words that I spoke to you while I was still with you, that everything written about me in the Law of Moses and the Prophets and the Psalms must be fulfilled&rdquo; (Luke 24:44).</p>",
    "17": "<p>&ldquo;My anger will burn against this place and will not be quenched.&rdquo; The unquenchable fire of divine judgment — <em>lōʾ tiḵbeh</em>. Jesus uses this exact language (&ldquo;unquenchable fire,&rdquo; <em>asbestos</em>) for Gehenna in Mark 9:43-48. The metaphor of judgment-as-unquenchable-fire originates in the Deuteronomic curse language (Deut 32:22; Jer 7:20) and is picked up in the eschatological discourse. The fire that falls on Jerusalem in 587 BCE is the historical form of the eschatological fire that judges all that is not of God.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The oracle pivots: &ldquo;As for the king of Judah who sent you.&rdquo; The same prophetic word that announces national judgment announces personal grace for the one who received the word with a humble heart. The structural distinction between corporate judgment and individual mercy recurs throughout Scripture: Noah amid the flood, Lot from Sodom, Rahab in Jericho. The gospel: the judgment that falls on sin falls on the one who bore our sin (2 Cor 5:21), while those who receive that word in humility are &ldquo;gathered to their ancestors in peace.&rdquo;</p>",
    "19": "<p>&ldquo;Because your heart was responsive (<em>wayyikkānēʿ lᵉḇāḇᵉkā</em>) and you humbled yourself before YHWH.&rdquo; <em>Kānāʿ</em> — the heart brought low, subdued. Only twice in the Deuteronomistic History is this said of a king: Ahab (1 Kgs 21:29) and Josiah. In both cases the humility defers judgment. Phil 2:7-8: Jesus &ldquo;emptied himself, taking the form of a servant... and humbled himself (<em>etapeinōsen</em>), becoming obedient to the point of death.&rdquo; Josiah&rsquo;s humility earns personal peace; Christ&rsquo;s humility earns the redemption of those who should face the judgment. The type and the antitype are distinguished by the scope of their achievement.</p>",
    "20": "<p>&ldquo;Your eyes will not see all the disaster I am going to bring on this place.&rdquo; The personal mercy in the context of the national judgment: Josiah will be gathered to his ancestors before the exile. This is the NT&rsquo;s &ldquo;blessed are those who die in the Lord from now on&rdquo; (Rev 14:13) — the righteous spared the sight of the full judgment. The peace promised to Josiah is the peace that passes through death rather than the peace that avoids it; he will die at Megiddo (23:29), but before the fall of Jerusalem he will be gathered. The death of the righteous before catastrophe is not tragedy but mercy.</p>"
  },
  "23": {
    "1": "<p>Josiah summons all the elders of Judah and Jerusalem. The covenant assembly — all the people from great to small — is the structural form of Sinai (Exod 19:7-8) and the Shechem renewal (Josh 24:1). The covenant is not made privately between God and the king; it requires the full assembly of the covenant people as witnesses and participants. The church as the covenant assembly (<em>ekklēsia</em> — called-out assembly) is the NT form of this gathering.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The king reads &ldquo;all the words of the Book of the Covenant&rdquo; in their ears. The covenant is orally ratified: the people must hear the words that bind them. The public reading of the covenant text is simultaneously the proclamation of its claims and the invitation to its commitment. Neh 8:3: Ezra reads from early morning until midday; the people listen attentively. The NT form: &ldquo;Faith comes from hearing, and hearing through the word of Christ&rdquo; (Rom 10:17). The oral, public word is the means of covenant entry.</p>",
    "3": "<p>&ldquo;The king stood beside the pillar and renewed the covenant before YHWH — to follow YHWH, keep his commandments, statutes, and decrees, with all his heart and all his soul.&rdquo; The Shema (Deut 6:4-5) enacted as covenant commitment: <em>bəkol lēḇ ûḇəkol nepeš</em>. Josiah is the king who formally commits the covenant community to the Shema standard. Heb 9:15: Christ is &ldquo;the mediator of a new covenant.&rdquo; The old covenant&rsquo;s mediation was through prophets, priests, and kings; the new covenant&rsquo;s mediation is through the one who is himself prophet, priest, and king — and who embodies the Shema commitment rather than merely committing to it.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Josiah removes all vessels for Baal, Asherah, and the astral cults from the temple and burns them in the Kidron Valley. The systematic purge begins from the center — the temple — and moves outward. The sequence of reform: interior first, then exterior. The reformation of the church&rsquo;s worship before the reformation of the culture. Jesus cleanses the temple before teaching the crowds; the inside of the cup must be cleaned first (Matt 23:26).</p>",
    "5": "<p>The <em>kᵉmārîm</em> (pagan priests) are dismissed and the astral cults from the towns of Judah to Geba and Beersheba are defiled. The geographic scope of the reform matches the geographic scope of the apostasy: what Manasseh spread throughout the land must be addressed throughout the land. The reach of the gospel matches the reach of sin: &ldquo;where sin increased, grace abounded all the more&rdquo; (Rom 5:20).</p>",
    "6": "<p>The Asherah pole — the idol placed inside the temple by Manasseh (21:7) — is removed, burned, ground to dust, and scattered on graves. The five-step destruction (remove, burn, grind, scatter, defile) is total and irreversible. The thoroughness of Josiah&rsquo;s desecration of the idolatrous cult objects is a type of the eschatological removal of all that is false: &ldquo;the works of the devil&rdquo; destroyed by the one who appeared for that purpose (1 John 3:8).</p>",
    "7": "<p>The quarters of the male shrine prostitutes in the temple — and the women who wove hangings for the Asherah — are torn down. The sexual cult embedded in the temple precinct is dismantled: the fertility religion that had colonized YHWH&rsquo;s house is expelled from it. The sexual immorality that is always the companion of idolatry (Rom 1:24-27: YHWH gives them up to &ldquo;dishonorable passions&rdquo; as a consequence of idol worship) is removed together with the idols that produced it.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Josiah centralizes the priesthood in Jerusalem, defiling the high places from Geba to Beersheba. The Deuteronomic centralization of worship — the single place YHWH has chosen (Deut 12:5) — is finally implemented. The scattering of worship sites is the spatial form of the scattering of loyalty; centralization embodies covenant singularity. John 4:21: Jesus will abolish the geographic requirement entirely — the new covenant worship is neither at Jerusalem nor at Gerizim but in spirit and truth.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The priests from the high places may eat unleavened bread with their brothers but may not serve at the altar. The pastoral accommodation of existing personnel within the reform: they are maintained but their service is restricted. The reform does not execute but restricts; it finds a place for the disqualified without enabling their disqualification. The wisdom of pastoral reform that distinguishes persons from their sins.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Josiah defiles Topheth in the Valley of Ben-Hinnom so that no one can sacrifice children to Molech. <em>Gê ben hinnōm</em> — the Valley of the Son of Hinnom — will contract in later Hebrew to <em>gêhinnōm</em>: Gehenna. Jesus uses &ldquo;Gehenna&rdquo; eleven times in the Gospels to describe the place of eschatological fire (Matt 5:22, 29-30; 10:28; 18:9; 23:15, 33; Mark 9:43-48; Luke 12:5). The place where children were burned becomes the image for the fire of final judgment. Josiah&rsquo;s defilement of the site writes its history into its name; the name Jesus invokes is the name of an actual place where actual children died for the sin of Israel. The eschatological fire is not an abstraction but has a historical address.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The horses dedicated to the sun are removed from the temple entrance. The solar cult with its horse processions — ANE royal religion that Manasseh had imported — is expelled. The &ldquo;horses of the sun&rdquo; are the most prestigious form of astral devotion: the king&rsquo;s war animals consecrated to the ruling celestial deity. The sovereignty of YHWH over the sun and stars — he created them (Gen 1:14-18); they do not rule (Deut 4:19) — is reasserted by removing them from the temple where they had no business being.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Roof altars of Ahaz and the altars of Manasseh are pulled down and the dust cast into the Kidron. The undoing of two generations of accumulation: what took decades to build is demolished in the reform. The temporal asymmetry of sin and repair — sin accrues slowly, reform must work against the grain — is the condition of every revival. The gospel addresses the entire accumulation of sin at once (Col 2:13-14: &ldquo;forgiving us all our trespasses, having canceled the record of debt&rdquo;).</p>",
    "13": "<p>The high places Solomon built on the Mount of Corruption (Mount of Olives south ridge) — for Ashtoreth, Chemosh, Milcom — are desecrated. These shrines had stood for over three centuries since Solomon built them. The reform that reaches back to Solomon is comprehensive; Josiah is not merely addressing recent apostasy but the foundational syncretism of the monarchy&rsquo;s greatest king. The Mount of Olives — the &ldquo;Mount of Corruption&rdquo; here — will be the place of Jesus&rsquo;s agony, arrest, and ascension. What was defiled by Solomon&rsquo;s apostasy will be sanctified by Christ&rsquo;s obedience.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The sacred stones smashed, the Asherah poles cut down, the sites covered with human bones. The threefold destruction (smash, cut, defile) is irreversible: covered with bones, a site cannot be used for worship again. The radical, irreversible cleansing is the type of the judgment that will not leave &ldquo;one stone upon another&rdquo; (Matt 24:2) — not merely partial reform but total demolition of what was built on the wrong foundation.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The Bethel altar — built by Jeroboam (1 Kgs 12:28-29), the founding apostasy of the northern kingdom — is demolished after three centuries. The prophecy of the man of God from Judah (1 Kgs 13:2) is fulfilled here: &ldquo;a son shall be born to the house of David, Josiah by name, and he shall sacrifice on you the bones of men.&rdquo; Three centuries between the word and its fulfillment demonstrates that YHWH&rsquo;s prophetic word is not merely predictive but historically determinative. 2 Pet 3:8-9: &ldquo;with the Lord one day is as a thousand years, and a thousand years as one day.&rdquo; The words of Christ will be fulfilled with the same precision and on YHWH&rsquo;s own timetable.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Josiah desecrates the Bethel altar with human bones taken from the hillside tombs — fulfilling exactly the 1 Kgs 13:2 prophecy (&ldquo;human bones shall be burned on it&rdquo;). The unintentional fulfillment of the prophetic word: Josiah did not set out to fulfill a 300-year-old prophecy; he was executing a reform. YHWH works through the free, purposeful actions of free moral agents to fulfill every word he has spoken. The determinism of prophecy and the freedom of the agent are not in competition.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The tomb of the man of God is preserved on Josiah&rsquo;s command: &ldquo;Let no one disturb his bones.&rdquo; The prophet whose disobedience led to his death but whose prophecy was entirely accurate has his burial honored by the king who fulfilled his prophecy. The separation between the prophet&rsquo;s personal failure and the prophetic word&rsquo;s reliability is preserved in Josiah&rsquo;s act: the prophet was flawed; the word was not. 2 Pet 1:21: &ldquo;prophecy never had its origin in the human will, but prophets, though human, spoke from God as they were carried along by the Holy Spirit.&rdquo;</p>",
    "18": "<p>Both tombs are preserved — the man of God from Judah and the Samarian prophet who buried him. The act of preservation honors the prophetic succession: the two prophets who bore witness to the Bethel judgment are jointly commemorated by the king who executed it. The community of faithful witness, even across human failure and sectarian division, is honored by the one who finally fulfills its testimony.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Josiah extends the reform into Samaria — former northern territory under Assyrian administration. The geographic reach of the covenant: the Davidic king acts as king over all Israel, not just Judah. The prophetic vision of the reunited twelve tribes (Ezek 37:15-22; Rev 21:12) is enacted spatially by Josiah&rsquo;s northward reform. Christ&rsquo;s commission is explicitly unlimited: &ldquo;all nations&rdquo; (Matt 28:19); the gospel that goes beyond Judah to Samaria (Acts 1:8) fulfills the Josian spatial expansion.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Josiah slaughters the priests of the northern high places on their own altars. The severe judgment on the agents of the northern apostasy contrasts with the milder treatment of the Judean high-place priests (v9). The greater the privilege and the longer the apostasy, the more severe the reckoning. Amos 3:2: &ldquo;You only have I known of all the families of the earth; therefore I will punish you for all your iniquities.&rdquo;</p>",
    "21": "<p>&ldquo;Celebrate the Passover to YHWH your God, as written in this Book of the Covenant.&rdquo; The Passover command comes at the end of the reform sequence — the purging precedes the feast. The sequence in the NT: the temple is cleansed before Jesus institutes the Lord&rsquo;s Supper (Matt 21:12-13 → 26:26-29). 1 Cor 5:7-8: &ldquo;Christ, our Passover lamb, has been sacrificed. Let us therefore celebrate the festival, not with the old leaven... but with the unleavened bread of sincerity and truth.&rdquo; The Passover restored under Josiah is the type of the Passover fulfilled in Christ.</p>",
    "22": "<p>&ldquo;Not since the days of the judges... had any such Passover been celebrated.&rdquo; The superlative Passover marks the maximum restoration of the covenant feast in Israel&rsquo;s history. Yet the next Passover narrative in the NT is the one in which Jesus says &ldquo;I have earnestly desired to eat this Passover with you before I suffer&rdquo; (Luke 22:15) and transforms it into the meal of the new covenant. The greatest OT Passover (Josiah&rsquo;s) is superseded by the one in which the Passover Lamb himself presides.</p>",
    "23": "<p>&ldquo;In the eighteenth year of King Josiah.&rdquo; The year of the book&rsquo;s discovery and the year of the Passover&rsquo;s restoration are the same year. The word rediscovered and the covenant feast restored are simultaneous: the recovery of Scripture and the recovery of worship are inseparable. The Reformation pattern: <em>sola scriptura</em> and the restoration of the Lord&rsquo;s Supper to the congregation are not accidents — they belong together.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Josiah removes mediums, spiritists, household gods, idols, and all detestable things from Judah — the precise reversal of Manasseh&rsquo;s 21:6 list. The symmetry is total: every item Manasseh introduced is removed by Josiah. The reform as comprehensive reversal of the apostasy. The NT form: the stripping away of every competing allegiance that defined the pre-conversion life (Eph 4:22-24: &ldquo;put off your old self... be renewed... put on the new self&rdquo;) — the comprehensive reversal of idolatry that characterizes genuine conversion.</p>",
    "25": "<p>&ldquo;Neither before nor after Josiah was there a king like him who turned to YHWH with all his heart, all his soul, and all his might, according to all the Law of Moses.&rdquo; The Shema (Deut 6:5) as the standard of covenantal faithfulness, applied supremely to Josiah. The superlative is immediately followed by the <em>ʾak</em> of v26. The greatest human embodiment of covenant faithfulness is still insufficient to undo the consequences of sin. Heb 10:4: &ldquo;it is impossible for the blood of bulls and goats to take away sins&rdquo; — the same impossibility applies to the most thorough reform. What is needed is not the best human performance of the covenant but the one who bears the covenant&rsquo;s curse and inaugurates the new one in his blood (Heb 9:15).</p>",
    "26": "<p>&ldquo;Nevertheless (<em>ʾak</em>), YHWH did not turn away from the burning of his great anger, which blazed against Judah because of all that Manasseh had done.&rdquo; The <em>ʾak</em> — &ldquo;nevertheless&rdquo; — is the most theologically decisive single word in the book. After the greatest covenant king, after the most thorough reform, after the Passover like none before, after the Shema lived out in full: nevertheless. Manasseh&rsquo;s sin is not reversible by Josiah&rsquo;s obedience. The innocent blood shed under Manasseh (21:16) cannot be atoned by subsequent righteousness. The <em>ʾak</em> points forward to the only remedy that can address what Josiah could not: the blood of the new covenant, shed for the forgiveness of sins (Matt 26:28) — the innocent blood that answers and covers all innocent blood previously shed.</p>",
    "27": "<p>&ldquo;I will remove Judah from my sight as I removed Israel. I will reject Jerusalem.&rdquo; The divine speech that cancels the election promise. But the cancellation is not final: Jer 31:31-34 promises a new covenant; Ezek 11:17-20 promises regathering; the same prophets who announce Jerusalem&rsquo;s rejection announce its restoration. The exile that follows is the crucifixion that precedes the resurrection — the apparent cancellation of the promise that is actually its fulfillment through death (John 12:24: &ldquo;unless a grain of wheat falls into the earth and dies, it remains alone; but if it dies, it bears much fruit&rdquo;).</p>",
    "28": "<p>The standard closing formula for Josiah. The theological evaluation (vv2, 25) has already been given; the historical summary follows. The contrast between the theological record (greatest king) and the historical outcome (dies at Megiddo, followed by collapse) sets up the NT resolution: the one about whom even greater things are said (Matt 3:17: &ldquo;This is my beloved Son, with whom I am well pleased&rdquo;) also dies before the restoration comes.</p>",
    "29": "<p>Pharaoh Necho kills Josiah at Megiddo. The greatest covenant king dies at the hands of a foreign power that was not even targeting him — Necho was on his way to help Assyria against Babylon, not to attack Judah. The death of the righteous king through the actions of foreign political powers pursuing their own agendas is the structure of Christ&rsquo;s death: Rome was pursuing its own political imperatives; Pilate found &ldquo;no fault&rdquo; (John 19:4); the death was not the execution of a criminal but the intersection of political convenience with divine purpose. Megiddo — <em>Harmāgedōn</em> in Rev 16:16 — accumulates eschatological significance as the site of the great king&rsquo;s death.</p>",
    "30": "<p>Josiah&rsquo;s body is brought to Jerusalem and buried in his own tomb. The <em>ʿam hāʾāreṣ</em> who installed him (21:24) now mourn him and install his son. The death of the righteous king produces grief in the covenant people — Zech 12:11-12 describes the eschatological mourning over the one pierced as being like &ldquo;the mourning for Josiah in the valley of Megiddo.&rdquo; Josiah&rsquo;s death at Megiddo becomes the OT&rsquo;s paradigm for the grief that attends the death of the righteous king.</p>",
    "31": "<p>Jehoahaz: twenty-three years old, three months. The son of the best king immediately shows that greatness cannot be inherited. The institutional transmission of covenant faithfulness without the personal transformation of the heart always fails in the next generation. The three-month reign is mercy: the covenant community is not subjected to a long apostasy from the house of the greatest king.</p>",
    "32": "<p>&ldquo;He did what was evil, just as his predecessors had done.&rdquo; The reversion formula after Josiah — the greatest praise in the history of the monarchy is immediately followed by the standard condemnation. The failure of reform to create lasting faithfulness without changed hearts is the OT&rsquo;s preparation for the promise of the new covenant: the law written on the heart (Jer 31:33), not merely taught to the children.</p>",
    "33": "<p>Necho imprisons Jehoahaz at Riblah and imposes tribute. The Davidic kingdom is now a vassal state — the independence of the covenant community under its covenant king is gone. The exile has begun, functionally, before the Babylonian exile: Egyptian domination replaces Davidic sovereignty. The messianic hope intensifies precisely when the Davidic line is most diminished — the prophets who speak most clearly of the coming king (Jer 23:5-6; Ezek 34:23-24; Zech 9:9) speak during and after the monarchy&rsquo;s collapse.</p>",
    "34": "<p>Pharaoh Necho renames Eliakim (<em>ʾĒlyāqîm</em> — &ldquo;God establishes&rdquo;) as Jehoiakim (<em>Yəhôyāqîm</em> — &ldquo;YHWH establishes&rdquo;). The foreign king substitutes YHWH&rsquo;s name into Judah&rsquo;s king&rsquo;s name as an act of ownership — he is asserting that the God of Israel&rsquo;s king exists at his pleasure. The humiliation of the Davidic line continues. Yet the messianic genealogy runs through these humiliated kings: Matt 1:11 names Jehoiakim (&ldquo;Josiah the father of Jechoniah&rdquo;) in the genealogy of Jesus. The Davidic line is not canceled by its humiliation; it is carried through it to its fulfillment.</p>",
    "35": "<p>Jehoiakim taxes the land to pay Necho&rsquo;s tribute. The extraction of resources from the covenant community by the covenant king, driven by foreign tribute demands — the inversion of the king&rsquo;s calling to protect and provide for the people (Deut 17:16-17 already prohibited the king from accumulating horses and wealth; now the king is accumulating tribute-obligations for a foreign master). The good king is defined by what he gives for the people; the bad king by what he takes from them.</p>",
    "36": "<p>Jehoiakim: twenty-five years old, eleven years. His reign spans the transition from Egyptian to Babylonian dominance (Carchemish, 605 BCE). The king who serves Egypt will find himself serving Babylon. The instability of political alliances as a substitute for covenant faithfulness: the alliance that seemed secure is overtaken by a larger power. Jer 2:18: &ldquo;What do you gain by going to Egypt to drink the waters of the Nile? Or what do you gain by going to Assyria to drink the waters of the Euphrates?&rdquo;</p>",
    "37": "<p>&ldquo;He did what was evil in the sight of YHWH, just as his predecessors had done.&rdquo; The final verse of chapter 23 ends on the formula of condemnation — the post-Josiah collapse is complete in two verses. The last word of the chapter is <em>ʾăḇōtāyw</em> — &ldquo;his fathers.&rdquo; The ancestors&rsquo; sin has overwhelmed the son&rsquo;s reform. The <em>ʾak</em> of v26 has worked itself out to its conclusion: Josiah&rsquo;s obedience could defer but not prevent the judgment that only the new covenant&rsquo;s mediator can finally absorb and reverse.</p>"
  }
}

